1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Torre Attack'!
This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the
Torre Attack. With the Torre Atack, White simplifies his life in the opening
and has an easy plan. It is more important to understand the plan and the
position then to memorize thousands of variations like in many other openings.
I did not analyze the absolute mainlines played umpteen times before, but the
lines that I found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with
many variations that have never been played before. While this course might be
useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {This is the most common move that Black can try
after 1. d4. In the queen's pawn opening, there is a wide range of options
that Black can choose from; moreover, he can be very tricky with the move
order, which could be a nasty surprise for White if he is not prepared in all
the variations. It is impossible to be up to date in all variations unless you
work on your openings at least a few hours every day and play a huge amount of
games, as professional players do. For example, Black can reach the same
position after 1... Nf6, as well as 1... d5 by playing the Nf6, e6, d5 moves
in any order. At super-GM level, Black players prefer the Nf6, e6 move order,
and only play d5 after Nf3 to avoid certain Queen's Gambit exchange lines with
Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {We have to start the variation with this move if we want to
make sure that our opponent cannot transpose into a Trompowsky line, which he
could do after 2.Bg5 with the move 2...Ne4.} e6 {White will face this move
very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian complex is extremely
popular, and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will choose this move before
playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards with this move. He wants to
develop his pieces according to the standard Torre-Attack plan. He intends to
play Nbd2, Nf3, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@ and c3.}
c5 {We will have a look at Black setups where Black plays ...d6 instead of ...
d5. Black immediately attacks the White center with c5 and makes some space
for his pieces. The 3... h6 move is a nuance in all these positions. Black can
play with or without this move, and the emerging positions will be almost
identical unless Black inserts the g5 move to chase the bishop further. We
will look at those lines later in the chapter.} 4. e3 Be7 {Black plays Be7 to
develop his pieces and prepare castling to the kingside. The main idea here is
to play Be7, b6, Bb7, d5, c5, and Nbd7.} 5. Nbd2 {White develops the knight to
its best square according to the main plan.} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. c3 Nc6
{This move is possible in this setup instead of d6-Nd7, and c6 might look a
better square for the knight, but it is not. The knight closes the long
diagonal for the bishop and does not have any good squares to go from here.} 9.
Qe2 {White progresses with his original plan.} cxd4 {This is an important move,
because if Black does not exchange on d4 now, then White can play e4 next.} 10.
exd4 Nd5 {This is again the typical play for Black. He would like to trade the
dark bishops to get more squares for the remaining pieces and decrease the
pressure on the kingside.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. g3 {Stopping Nf4. With this move,
White opens up the long light diagonal h1-a8, but you don't have to worry
about that because Black doesn't have enough pieces to attack White king any
time soon. It is much more important to prevent the Black knight from getting
the f4-square.} d6 13. Rfe1 Rfe8 14. a4 a6 15. Nc4 {The variation ends in a
very similar position that we have just seen. The only difference is that the
knight is on c6 instead of d7. The position is still about equal, maybe a
little better for White, because the knight is better placed on d7 than on c6.
White plays according to the original plan. The next move will be Nfd2 and
then at some point Nce3, with the idea of playing on the queenside.} *

