useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {This is the most common move that Black can try
after 1. d4. There is a wide range of options Black can choose from in the
queen's pawn opening main and sidelines. Moreover, he can be very tricky with
the move order, which could be a nasty surprise for White if he is not
prepared in all the variations. It is impossible to be up to date in all
variations unless you work on your openings at least a few hours every day and
play a huge amount of games, as professional players do. For example, Black
can reach the same position after 1... Nf6, as well as 1... d5 by playing the
Nf6, e6, d5 moves in any order. At super-GM level, Black players prefer the
Nf6, e6 move order, and only play d5 after Nf3, to avoid certain Queen's
Gambit exchange lines with Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {We have to start the variation with
this move if we want to make sure that our opponent cannot transpose into a
Trompowsky line, which he could do after 2.Bg5 with the move 2...Ne4.} e6 {
White will face this move very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian
complex is extremely popular, and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will
also choose this move before playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards
with this move. He wants to develop his pieces according to the standard
Torre-Attack plan. He intends to play Nbd2, Nf3, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or
sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@ and c3.} c5 {We will have a look at Black setups
where Black plays ...d6 instead of ...d5. Black immediately attacks the White
center with c5 and makes some space for his pieces. The 3... h6 move is a
nuance in all these positions. Black can play with or without this move, and
the emerging positions will be almost identical unless Black inserts the g5
move to chase the bishop further. We will look at those lines later in the
chapter.} 4. e3 Qb6 {This is the most aggressive move that Black can play to
put pressure on the b2 and d4 pawns. Now White can either protect the b2-pawn
or sacrifice it for the initiative. In our attacking repertoire, we will only
look at the second option, as White's play is so active after the pawn
sacrifice, that is is hard not to play it.} 5. Nbd2 {White brings the knight
into play and now Black's only chance for play is to take the offered pawn.}
cxd4 6. exd4 Qxb2 {This is Black's most aggressive option. Black takes the
pawn and intends to defend his position, hoping to reach a better endgame with
the pawn up.} 7. Bd3 {White has to play actively to prove that the pawn
sacrifice is sound, as there is no immediate win. The best way to continue is
to quickly develop the pieces and castle, after which White can start
attacking the Black queen and put pressure on the center.} Nc6 {This is
developing move that looks fine, but allows Nc4, so White can immediately
start attacking the Black queen.} 8. Rb1 {White has a clear target, and would
like to get as many tempi as he can to put all the pieces on the best squares
to increase the pressure.} Qxa2 9. Nc4 {The Black queen has run out of squares,
and Ra1 is threatened.} Qa4 {The queen looks very ugly on the a4-square, but
Black doesn't have an alternative.} 10. O-O d5 {Black has to slow down the
White initiative and tries to close the center.} 11. Nce5 {The best square for
the knight.} Qa5 {As in many lines with Qxb2, the queen can easily get trapped
or exposed. Black has to make some precise moves, which are often pretty hard
to find.} 12. Nxc6 {White has finished his development and has to keep pushing.
Black is two pawns up, but behind in development, with the king still in the
center. White takes on c6, then wants to put the other knight to e5 and target
the Black c6-pawn.} bxc6 13. Ne5 Qc7 {Black might want to develop his bishop
to e7, but to do that, he has to protect the c6-pawn first.} 14. Qf3 {The
White queen now joins in attacking the f6-square.} Be7 {Black has to protect
the knight, as Bxf6 and then Qxf6 would be disastrous.} 15. Nxc6 {White takes
back a pawn while retaining the pressure.} O-O {Black has to castle to get out
of the attack in the center.} 16. Nxe7+ {Now White starts to play on the
kingside. Both the bishops and the queen attack the Black kingside. The idea
is clear. White wants to play Qg3-h4 with a direct attack on the Black king.
It's far from easy to defend here.} Qxe7 17. Qg3 a5 {Black tries to exchange
the light-squared bishops but this is too slow.} 18. Qh4 {White has enormous
pressure. It's very hard for Black to defend this position. For example, let's
take a look at h6.} h6 19. Bxh6 gxh6 20. Qxh6 Ba6 21. Bxa6 Rxa6 22. Qg5+ Kh8
23. Qh4+ Kg7 24. Rb3 {And White is winning.} *

