1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Torre Attack'!
This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the
Torre Attack. With the Torre Atack, White simplifies his life in the opening
and has an easy plan. It is more important to understand the plan and the
position then to memorize thousands of variations like in many other openings.
I did not analyze the absolute mainlines played umpteen times before, but the
lines that I found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with
many variations that have never been played before. While this course might be
useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {This is the most common move that Black can try
after 1. d4. There is a wide range of options Black can choose from in the
queen's pawn opening main and sidelines. Moreover, he can be very tricky with
the move order, which could be a nasty surprise for White if he is not
prepared in all the variations. It is impossible to be up to date in all
variations unless you work on your openings at least a few hours every day and
play a huge amount of games, as professional players do. For example, Black
can reach the same position after 1... Nf6, as well as 1... d5 by playing the
Nf6, e6, d5 moves in any order. At super-GM level, Black players prefer the
Nf6, e6 move order, and only play d5 after Nf3, to avoid certain Queen's
Gambit exchange lines with Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {We have to start the variation with
this move if we want to make sure that our opponent cannot transpose into a
Trompowsky line, which he could do after 2.Bg5 with the move 2...Ne4.} e6 {
White will face this move very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian
complex is extremely popular, and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will
also choose this move before playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards
with this move. He wants to develop his pieces according to the standard
Torre-Attack plan. He intends to play Nbd2, Nf3, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or
sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@ and c3.} c5 {We will have a look at Black setups
where Black plays ...d6 instead of ...d5. Black immediately attacks the White
center with c5 and makes some space for his pieces. The 3... h6 move is a
nuance in all these positions. Black can play with or without this move, and
the emerging positions will be almost identical unless Black inserts the g5
move to chase the bishop further. We will look at those lines later in the
chapter.} 4. e3 Qb6 {This is the most aggressive move that Black can play to
put pressure on the b2 and d4 pawns. Now White can either protect the b2-pawn
or sacrifice it for the initiative. In our attacking repertoire, we will only
look at the second option, as White's play is so active after the pawn
sacrifice, that is is hard not to play it.} 5. Nbd2 {White brings the knight
into play and now Black's only chance for play is to take the offered pawn.}
Qxb2 6. Bd3 {The most energetic reply. White wants to develop all minor pieces
and castle quickly. Black takes the pawn but White wins a few tempi by chasing
the Black queen whilst developing the pieces much faster than Black. In these
positions White often sacrifices a second pawn for huge initiative and
positional compensation. It's hard to suggest these lines for Black because
White's play is incredibly easy and Black has a very hard time trying to find
dozens of precise moves just to stay in the game.} d5 7. Bxf6 {This is a very
important capture. White takes the only developed Black piece and destroys the
Black kingside pawn chain. Also, now the knight does not defend the d5-square,
so White can open the game in the center following c4 and get huge initiative.}
gxf6 8. c4 {This move completely opens the center after the exchange on the f6,
so the White pieces get much more space to squeeze Black.} Qa3 {This is
probably the best move in the position. Now Black wins some time by attacking
the bishop and the queen is not that exposed anymore.} 9. Be2 {The best choice
for the bishop is to go back to e2.} dxc4 {With this move, Black tries not to
allow White to create an isolated d5 pawn with cxd5.} 10. Nxc4 {The drawback
of Black's last move is that now the knight can occupy the c4-square.} Qc3+ {
This is a blunder. It may look like the queen is getting away after giving a
check, it can be easily trapped on c3.} 11. Nfd2 {White defends, and also
brings yet another piece to the queenside to try and capture the Black queen.}
cxd4 {Black intends to clear some squares for the queen.} 12. Rc1 {White
improves his position whilst attacking the Black queen.} Qb4 13. a3 Qe7 14. Ne4
{The Black queen managed to escape but White has huge initiative.} Nc6 15.
Ncd6+ {Black couldn't stop this annoying check. The White pieces are just too
active.} Kd8 16. O-O {White calmly finishes development and gets ready to
crush the Black position. For example: 16...Qd7 17.Rxc6 bxc6 18.Qxd4 and White
is winning because Black cannot defend against the threats of Qxf6 and Nxf7.} *

