Nf6, e6 move order, and only play d5 after Nf3, to avoid certain Queen's
Gambit exchange lines with Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {We have to start the variation with
this move if we want to make sure that our opponent cannot transpose into a
Trompowsky line, which he could do after 2.Bg5 with the move 2...Ne4.} e6 {
White will face this move very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian
complex is extremely popular, and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will
also choose this move before playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards
with this move. He wants to develop his pieces according to the standard
Torre-Attack plan. He intends to play Nbd2, Nf3, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or
sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@ and c3.} c5 {We will have a look at Black setups
where Black plays ...d6 instead of ...d5. Black immediately attacks the White
center with c5 and makes some space for his pieces. The 3... h6 move is a
nuance in all these positions. Black can play with or without this move, and
the emerging positions will be almost identical unless Black inserts the g5
move to chase the bishop further. We will look at those lines later in the
chapter.} 4. e3 Qb6 {This is the most aggressive move that Black can play to
put pressure on the b2 and d4 pawns. Now White can either protect the b2-pawn
or sacrifice it for the initiative. In our attacking repertoire, we will only
look at the second option, as White's play is so active after the pawn
sacrifice, that is is hard not to play it.} 5. Nbd2 {White brings the knight
into play and now Black's only chance for play is to take the offered pawn.}
Qxb2 6. Bd3 {The most energetic reply. White wants to develop all minor pieces
and castle quickly. Black takes the pawn but White wins a few tempi by chasing
the Black queen whilst developing the pieces much faster than Black. In these
positions White often sacrifices a second pawn for huge initiative and
positional compensation. It's hard to suggest these lines for Black because
White's play is incredibly easy and Black has a very hard time trying to find
dozens of precise moves just to stay in the game.} d5 7. Bxf6 {This is a very
important capture. White takes the only developed Black piece and destroys the
Black kingside pawn chain. Also, now the knight does not defend the d5-square,
so White can open the game in the center following c4 and get huge initiative.}
gxf6 8. c4 {This move completely opens the center after the exchange on the f6,
so the White pieces get much more space to squeeze Black.} Qc3 {This is an
interesting move. Black wins some time by attacking the White bishop and hopes
to retreat with the queen via a5.} 9. Be2 {Again, like in the ...Qa3 variation,
this is the best square for the light-squared bishop.} Nc6 {Developing move
that also puts some pressure on the White center and the d4-pawn.} 10. Rc1 {
Thematic move. White improves the position of his rook and attacks the Black
queen.} Qa5 {This square feels a little more natural for the Black queen.} 11.
cxd5 {White is ahead in development, so he opens the game.} exd5 12. O-O c4 {
Black tries to keep the position closed and finish his development, but this
plan is doomed to fail.} 13. e4 {White immediately blows the center open and
takes the initiative.} Nb4 14. exd5 b5 15. Re1 {White is better. The Black
king is still in the center and Bxc4 is in the air. White is fully developed
and ready for action, whilst Black only moved his knight and queen, both
bishops and rooks together with the king are on their original squares. Also,
every single Black pawn is weak. It is not easy to play in this position with
the Black pieces.} *

