Thematic move. White improves the position of his rook and attacks the Black
queen.} Qa5 {This square feels a little more natural for the Black queen.} 11.
cxd5 {White is ahead in development, so he opens the game.} exd5 12. O-O Qxa2 {
Black takes the second pawn.} 13. e4 {The Black king is still in the middle,
so White immediately blows up the center without counting the pawns.} Be7 {
This bishop move is not enough to stop the White storm, but either exchange in
the center is bad and ends in an even better position for White.} 14. Ra1 {
White forces the Black queen away from the protection of the d5-pawn.} Qb2 15.
exd5 {And now White takes on d5.} Nxd4 16. d6 {This move demonstrates how big
the White positional advantage is. The pawn cannot be taken because of Nc4 but
it turns out, there is no good alternative !} Bxd6 17. Nc4 {This move grants
White a clear advantage. The best Black can do is to give up his queen.} Qxe2
18. Re1 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Rg8+ 20. Kh1 Qxe1+ 21. Qxe1+ Be7 22. Nd6+ {At the end
of this forced line White is better. Even though Black has a rook, a bishop,
and three pawns for the queen, he is completely undeveloped and almost all of
his pawns are weak. The Black king has to go to f8, after which Rxa7 will get
a big advantage for White.} *

