Black kingside pawn chain. Also, now the knight does not defend the d5-square,
so White can open the game in the center following c4 and get huge initiative.}
gxf6 8. c4 {This move completely opens the center after the exchange on the f6,
so the White pieces get much more space to squeeze Black.} cxd4 {There is huge
tension in the center that Black needs to handle somehow. There are a few
possibilities. The first one is to take on d4.} 9. Rb1 {White activates the
rook on the b-file again.} Qxa2 {This move is possible, and there is no
immediate win for White, but it does look scary. The queen is misplaced on a2.}
10. Nxd4 {The general idea is to take on d4 with the knight, castle, and then
start playing on the queenside.} Nc6 {Black is lagging in development so he
has to start bringing his pieces into play. It would also be preferable for
Black to start exchanging pieces to decrease the pressure.} 11. Nxc6 {White
has a clear and easy plan. Exchange the only developed Black piece and then
open the game in the center.} bxc6 12. cxd5 Bd7 {Here we have a nice picture
again. The Black position is so bad, that taking on d5 with either of the
pawns would lose almost instantly, and 12...Qxd5 would run into 13.Be4.} 13.
Bc4 {White attacks the queen and improves the position of the light-squared
bishop.} Qa5 14. dxe6 {White opens the game and castles with a clear advantage.
} Bxe6 15. O-O {Again, White is a pawn down, but Black has more weaknesses
than what he could defend. It could easily happen that White would be a pawn
up in the next couple of moves. All the Black pawns are weak and White can put
a lot of pressure on them. Also, the Black king will never be safe. White has
huge initiative and better position.} *

