1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Torre Attack'!
This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the
Torre Attack. With the Torre Atack, White simplifies his life in the opening
and has an easy plan. It is more important to understand the plan and the
position then to memorize thousands of variations like in many other openings.
I did not analyze the absolute mainlines played umpteen times before, but the
lines that I found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with
many variations that have never been played before. While this course might be
useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {This is the most common answer to 1. d4. There
is a wide range of options for Black to choose from in the queen's pawn
opening main and sidelines, spiced up with subtle move order transpositions,
that could be a nasty surprise for White if he is not prepared in all the
variations. It is impossible to be up to date in all lines unless you study
openings for a few hours every day and play a huge number of games, as
professional players do. For example, Black can reach the same position after
1... Nf6, as well as 1. ..d5 by playing the Nf6, e6, d5 moves in any order. At
super-GM level, Black players prefer the Nf6, e6 move order and only play d5
after Nf3, to avoid certain Queen's Gambit exchange lines with Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {
We have to start with this move if we want to make sure that our opponent
cannot transpose into a Trompowsky line after 2. Bg5, Ne4.} e6 {White will
face this move very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian complex are
extremely popular and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will also choose
this move before playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards with this move.
He wants to develop his pieces according to the standard Torre-Attack plan. He
intends to play Nbd2, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@
and c3.} h6 {This is a nuance that does not make a huge difference, in my
opinion, but Black might play it, so it is good to know how to advance.
Regardless of the move h6, White should think the same way as in the other
lines. The benefit of this move for Black is that after Bh4, the bishop cannot
go back to the queenside. However, this is not a problem here for White and
should play the move anyway.} 4. Bh4 {White keeps the tension on the h4-d8
diagonal. If Black wants to capture the bishop, he has to play g5 and Nh5,
making the kingside vulnerable in the long run.} c5 {This is the most popular
Black continuation. The idea is to strike in the center immediately and open
the b6-square for the queen to put some pressure on d4 and, now that the White
dark-squared bishop is on the other side of the board, also attack b2. You
will often see a pawn sacrifice on b2 in similar variations in exchange for
quick development and initiative. If Black plays ....d5 here, we would
transpose to a Pseudo-Trompovsky variation.} 5. e3 {White plays according to
the original plan. Our move order is d4, Nf3, Bg5, and e3 - with the
additional Bh4 here.} cxd4 {The first one of Black's two possibilities here is
to capture on d4. This will result in a half-open c-file and stops White from
playing c3 to be able to recapture with it on d4 and play e4 later on. So, if
Black wants to exchange on d4 at all, now is the time, when the White pawn is
still on the c2-square.} 6. exd4 Be7 {Black now has a clear plan as well, and
even though the next moves are not forced by any means, they have to be played.
Black can play them in any move order, but White can also do the same. The
idea here is to solidify with ...d6, then bring the light-squared bishop to
the a8-h1 long diagonal, and castle.} 7. Nbd2 {White plans to put the
light-squared bishop on d3, Nbd2, c3, Qe2, and castle next. White can also
choose any move order, but it is preferable to play Nbd2 first to allow Nc4 in
case Black wants to slot in ...Qb6 at any point. In the spirit of our
repertoire, White will achieve a beautiful, easy-to-play position again.} b6 8.
Bd3 Bb7 9. c3 O-O 10. Qe2 d6 {This move prepares ...Nbd7 and is much better
than 10...Nc6.} 11. O-O Nh5 {This is the correct move. Black's idea is to
exchange the dark-squared bishops to decrease the tension on the d8-h4
diagonal and possibly get the f4-square for the knight.} 12. Bg3 Nd7 {The
knight is much better placed on d7 because it can get to f6, and the extended
diagonal stays open for the light-squared bishop.} 13. a4 {With only a slight
advantage for White. The pieces are a little bit better placed and coordinated.
There is a clear plan to play the Nc4, Nfd2, Ne3, and to exert pressure to the
center and queenside.} *

