1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Torre Attack'!
This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the
Torre Attack. With the Torre Atack, White simplifies his life in the opening
and has an easy plan. It is more important to understand the plan and the
position then to memorize thousands of variations like in many other openings.
I did not analyze the absolute mainlines played umpteen times before, but the
lines that I found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with
many variations that have never been played before. While this course might be
useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {This is the most common answer to 1. d4. There
is a wide range of options for Black to choose from in the queen's pawn
opening main and sidelines, spiced up with subtle move order transpositions,
that could be a nasty surprise for White if he is not prepared in all the
variations. It is impossible to be up to date in all lines unless you study
openings for a few hours every day and play a huge number of games, as
professional players do. For example, Black can reach the same position after
1... Nf6, as well as 1. ..d5 by playing the Nf6, e6, d5 moves in any order. At
super-GM level, Black players prefer the Nf6, e6 move order, and only play d5
after Nf3 to avoid certain Queen's Gambit exchange lines with Nge2.} 2. Nf3 {
We have to start with this move if we want to make sure that our opponent
cannot transpose into a Trompowsky line after 2. Bg5, Ne4.} e6 {White will
face this move very often, as the queen's, Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian the complex
is trendy, and some advocates of the Queen's Gambit will also choose this move
before playing d5.} 3. Bg5 {White will show his cards with this move. He wants
to develop his pieces according to the standard Torre-Attack plan. He intends
to play Nbd2, e3, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@or sometimes Be2@@EndBracket@@ and c3.}
h6 {This is a nuance that does not make a huge difference, in my opinion, but
Black might play it, so it is good to know how to advance. Regardless of the
move h6, White should think the same way as in the other lines. The benefit of
this move for Black is that after Bh4, the bishop cannot go back to the
queenside. However, this is not a problem here for White and should play the
move anyway.} 4. Bh4 {White keeps the tension on the h4-d8 diagonal. If Black
wants to capture the bishop, he has to play g5 and Nh5 making the kingside
vulnerable in the long run.} g5 {This is Black's most direct and aggressive
option with the clear intention of taking the dark-squared bishop. The
drawback is that these pawn moves weaken the kingside. It is also worth
mentioning that the Black setup with the pawns on e6 and d7 instead of d6 and
e7, like in the King's Indian, is not particularly useful for Black.} 5. Bg3
Ne4 {Black immediately attacks the dark-squared bishop.} 6. Nbd2 {This is
White's standard developing move, which is also the best now.} Nxg3 7. hxg3 Bg7
8. c3 {The White setup is the same in almost all positions, so just develop
the pieces on the best squares using the typical structure. It is worth noting
that we should move the e-pawn last. In the next move, we will see why.} Nc6 {
Black has two options. One of them is to develop the knight to c6 and bring
the light-squared bishop to d7. The other one is to fianchetto the bishop.} 9.
e4 {It is best to play e4 in one move if Black allows it. This is why White
has to pay attention to the move order and play Nbd2 and c3 first and only
then move the e-pawn. Now White builds a strong pawn center.} d6 10. Nc4 {This
is a positional prophylactic move that prepares the retreat of the f3 knight
to the d2 square in case Black plays ...g4 in the future.} Bd7 11. Be2 Qe7 {
This move is much more solid than 11...g4. The best flow of actions for Black
is to develop the pieces and castle before taking any further actions on the
kingside.} 12. d5 {White gets more space and takes control over the important
d5 central square, after which Black will be tied up in defense.} exd5 {This
is the alternative to 12...Ne5. It is not a particularly good idea for Black
to open the position here, but some players might try it.} 13. exd5 Ne5 14.
Nfxe5 {Now after a few precise but straightforward moves White will get the
advantage.} Bxe5 {Taking with the bishop is better, because after 14...dxe5
the dark-squared bishop is locked out of play on g7, and White has the strong
d5-d6 break supported by the c4-knight.} 15. O-O O-O 16. Re1 Rae8 17. Bd3 {
White has excellent prospects. With the f4 threat that wins the piece, White
has a clear target. If Black plays 17...Qf6 to stop f4, then 18.Ne3 will get
the advantage.} *

