would usually go with the ...d6 move. Nevertheless, I will show how to deal
with the ...d5 lines if Black chooses to be tricky.} 5. c3 {This is the move
that we will make regardless of Black playing ...d6 or ...d5. Take a mental
note that the move order that we want to play against 1... Nf6 is d4, Nf3, Bg5,
Nbd2, c3. We would like to get easily playable positions with a clear plan and
without too much theory.} O-O {Black castles before starting to play for some
activity.} 6. e3 {White secures the d4-square and prepares the development of
the last minor piece.} b6 {This reply is quite common at the club level. Black
wants to place the light-squared bishop on the long diagonal and then play ...
c5 which will be supported by the b6-pawn.} 7. Be2 {The square for the
light-squared bishop.} c5 {This move is more common. The b6-pawn supports the
c5 advance and Black will play according to his plan and bring the
light-squared bishop to b7 later on.} 8. h3 {This move secures the g4-square
and vacates h2 for the dark-squared bishop.} Nc6 {This is the best square for
the knight, as it keeps an eye on the d4 and e5 squares from here.} 9. O-O {It
is a good idea to secure the king before taking action.} Bb7 {This bishop is
Black's last undeveloped piece and b7 is the most obvious square for it.} 10.
Bh4 {The idea is to secure the b8-h2 diagonal but we also want to be able to
play f4 following Ne5.} Re8 {Black is ready to play ...e5 and White has to
react.} 11. Ne5 {White cannot allow Black to play ...e5. In these positions,
when Black prepares the e5-break White must play Ne5, otherwise Black
immediately reaches equality.} Nxe5 {This capture is the best reply. Black
decreases the pressure by exchanging knights. The alternative could be for
example 11...Rc8 but then 12.f4 is strong, after which White would get a firm
grip of the e5-square.} 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 {White has a slight advantage and
the easier to play position.} *

