1. d4 {Hello, dear chess friends! Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: Torre Attack'!
This 'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the
Torre Attack. With the Torre Atack, White simplifies his life in the opening
and has an easy plan. It is more important to understand the plan and the
position then to memorize thousands of variations like in many other openings.
I did not analyze the absolute mainlines played umpteen times before, but the
lines that I found interesting. It is a unique and creative repertoire with
many variations that have never been played before. While this course might be
useful even for professional players, I aimed to deliver a repertoire to the
strong non-professional players, club players, and absolute beginners. I hope
you enjoy this overview!} Nf6 {White faces this move more than 60% of the time
after 1. d4. Black can choose some tricky move orders in the main lines, which
could create problems for White if he is not well prepared and ready for all
sidelines. Nowadays, if you are not a professional player who works on the
opening for at least a few hours each day and plays a huge amount of the games,
you will find it very hard to prepare against all possible variations, lines
and move orders. The repertoire that I present in this book has been my
repertoire for the last 5-10 years. When I was younger and played a lot, I
studied thousands of lines in 1. e4 openings. This is OK if you are a
professional player who not only studies but also plays continuously during
the year. Because even if you put in the time to study, without playing, you
will forget most of it and will have a really tough time to remember anything
over the board. I speak from personal experience. ;- Usually, people only have
limited time to spend on a hobby, and if this is the case with you, then its
not worth spending your precious time learning openings exclusively and
completely neglecting all other aspects of the game. You have to find a
balance between studying openings and working on other essential things as
well. With this repertoire, I managed to considerably cut the time that I have
to spend on the opening. White usually tries to reach the following setup if
possible: d4, Nf3, Bg5, e3. The lines and variations are easy to learn; the
emerging positions are understandable and easy to play with clear plans for
the middlegame.} 2. Nf3 {It is essential to play this move first to get the
setup that we would like to achieve. White could also play 2. Bg5 and
transpose to variations that we will discuss, but if Black plays Ne4, then
White has to play the Trompowsky, which is not the topic of this book. During
the past five years, I have been playing both of the Bg5, and Nf3 move orders,
transposing to either the Torre attack or the Trompowsky, and get great
results with both openings.} g6 {Black has to show his plan with his second
move. In this chapter, we will look at Kings-Indian and Grunfeld Defense
structures.} 3. Bg5 {White now plays Bg5, one move later than in the positions
with 1... d5. The idea is to develop the dark-squared bishop before pushing
the pawn to e3 securing the central d4-square.} Bg7 {Black always plays this
move after he chose to play ...g6. The idea is to bring the bishop to the long
diagonal. This move also protects the knight on f6, avoiding a break in the
pawn structure in case White would take on f6 next.} 4. Nbd2 {Black still
hasn't shown his intentions and could play either ...d6 or ...d5. Nbd2 allows
White to play e4 if Black does not play ...d5.} d5 {After castling, Black
would usually go with the ...d6 move. Nevertheless, I will show how to deal
with the ...d5 lines if Black chooses to be tricky.} 5. c3 {This is the move
that we will make regardless of Black playing ...d6 or ...d5. Take a mental
note that the move order that we want to play against 1... Nf6 is d4, Nf3, Bg5,
Nbd2, c3. We would like to get easily playable positions with a clear plan and
without too much theory.} O-O {Black castles before starting to play for some
activity.} 6. e3 {White secures the d4-square and prepares the development of
the last minor piece.} Ne4 {This is an active move but I don't like it. Black
should finish his development before he starts active operations.} 7. Nxe4 {
White takes the knight and leaves Black with a potentially weak pawn on e4.}
dxe4 8. Nd2 {The e4-pawn is immediately under attack.} h6 {This is not enough
to get equality. In the main course we will discuss Black's alternatives.} 9.
Bh4 c5 {Black tries to open the game in the center and potentially sacrifice
the e4-pawn for activity.} 10. Nxe4 {White simply takes the pawn. Black gets
some activity but White can even sacrifice a piece later for a great position.}
cxd4 11. exd4 f5 {Now Black can trap the dark-squared bishop with g5 and f4.}
12. Nc5 {A critical move after which White is just better. The bishop will be
sacrificed on the g5-square.} g5 13. Bxg5 {White gives a piece for a couple of
pawns and opens the position of the Black king.} hxg5 14. Bc4+ e6 15. O-O {
White has a big advantage. Black took the bishop, but White got two pawns and
at least one more on e6 will fall next after Re1. The Black king will be
vulnerable for the rest of the game.} *

