diagonal, and also attack the c5-pawn, which might become a very important
tactical resource in some of the variations.} h6 {This is not a good move. Now
Black loses a pawn by force. This is a common mistake that inexperienced
players might make here, so it is worth remembering the tactical solution to
get the clear pawn.} 11. Bxf6 {Now White will just take a pawn with a clear
advantage and no compensation for Black.} exf6 {11...Bxf6 12.Qe3 forks the c5-
and h6-pawns. Instead, 11... exf6 is Black's try not to lose a pawn, but now
his position is just very bad. The dark-squared bishop will never play again
and White has the upper hand to do whatever he wants. This move is a
positional suicide.} 12. Nh4 {It is very important to understand and play this
move. White has to control Black's f6-f5 break to cripple his position.
Without f6-f5, Black will just be without any play and White could even play
f5 himself, in which case the g7-bishop would become a tall pawn.} Ne7 {Black
hopes to play f5, but it will not be possible even after this move.} 13. f4 {
White plays according to his plan and takes more space in the center and
kingside. Also, f4-f5 is in the air.} g5 {This is Black's last hope to open
the position on the kingside to bring the dark-squared bishop back into play.}
14. Nf5 {White has to move the knight. Following an exchange on f5, the pawn
will paralyze the dark-squared bishop for a long time and vacate the great
e4-square for the knight.} Nxf5 15. exf5 Bd7 16. fxg5 hxg5 17. Ne4 {And White
gets a nice positional advantage again. The knight on e4 is a much better
piece than the Black dark-squared bishop and it is hard to see a way to
improve the Black position. He will suffer for a long time.} *

