players will likely play this move against the Torre. It is more dynamic than
d5 because Black's main plan is to break in the center with e7-e5. After ...d5,
Black usually tries to play c7-c5 later on.} 6. e4 {This is our starting point
in this variation. The upcoming positions will be Pirc Defence positions
rather than King's Indian. This is great for White because some Black players
will be caught out having to play unfamiliar lines against e4, which are
outside their comfort zone.} Nbd7 {This move is related to the plan to push
e7-e5. Black intends to fight for the center to get some space and fight for
activity.} 7. Bd3 {As in many lines in this repertoire, the idea is to use the
same piece placement where possible. In this system, the light-squared bishop
belongs to the d3-square to protect the e4-pawn.} e5 {The immediate ...e5
works, because the d7-knight supports the pawn.} 8. O-O exd4 {Black wants to
reduce the tension in the center.} 9. Nxd4 {I prefer this move here as it
makes White's life easier. 9.cxd4 is also possible, but it is better to get
good and easy-to-play positions without too many Black options. If White takes
with the pawn, then Black could counter strike with ...c5 exploiting the
misplaced position of the d2-knight. After 9. Nxd4 White has a stable position
in the center without natural breaks from the other side. This reduces Black's
activity, and now he has to finish his development by playing solid but
passive moves again.} Ne5 {Black plays actively in the center and attacks the
d3-bishop immediately. The drawback is that this knight on e5 can be chased
away with f4 with tempo and initiative.} 10. Bc2 {The best square for the
White light-squared bishop. He has to defend the e4-pawn to keep the center
together.} h6 {Black pushes away the White dark-squared bishop, also thinking
about a possible g5 move to secure the knight on e5 and stop White's f4 plan.}
11. Bh4 c5 {A typical counter-strike in the center in this position and some
positions in the King's Indian. Black attacks the d4-knight and gets some
space with this move, but it also weakens the d6-pawn, so Black has to be
careful.} 12. Ne2 {The best square for this knight.} Re8 {Maintains pressure
on the e4-pawn.} 13. Re1 {The rook defends the e4-pawn and supports a future
e4-e5 break.} g5 {This is an excellent alternative to Bd7-c6. Black secures
the great knight on e5 and obstructs White's f4 plan. The drawback of this
move is that it weakens the f5-square.} 14. Bg3 d5 {This is the alternative to
14...Nh5 which is analyzed in the main course. Black immediately strikes in
the center to avoid being pressured on the light squares, especially on d5 and
f5 following moves like Ng3 and Nf1-e3. However, Black is still not fully
developed and White can take advantage of energetic play.} 15. Bxe5 {White has
to be aggressive and take action in the center because if Black manages to
stabilize his position, White could be in trouble.} Rxe5 16. Nc4 {White
exchanged the active knight on e5 for his dark-squared bishop and gave Black
the bishop pair just to seize the initiative and get some tempi to improve the
position of his pieces.} Re8 17. exd5 {White opens the center utilizing his
better piece development.} Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. Rad1 Be6 20. Nd6 Re7 21. Bf5
{Up to this move almost everything is forced. White managed to activate his
pieces and get some nice squares for them. Black's pieces are not very well
coordinated. The White knight on d6 and the rooks on d1 and e1 exert pressure
on the Black position. White has a long term positional advantage and Black
has to try to find a way to decrease the pressure and exchange a few pieces to
reach equality. In the meantime, White would like to increase the pressure
with Ng3 to get to the e4 or even f5 or h5 squares next.} *

