after 1..., Nf6, our move order is Nf3, Bg5, Nbd2, and c3.} d6 {King's Indian
players will likely play this move against the Torre. It is more dynamic than
d5 because Black's main plan is to break in the center with e7-e5. After ...d5,
Black usually tries to play c7-c5 later on.} 6. e4 {This is our starting point
in this variation. The upcoming positions will be Pirc Defence positions
rather than King's Indian. This is great for White because some Black players
will be caught out having to play unfamiliar lines against e4, which are
outside their comfort zone.} Nc6 {If Black wants to play e7-e5 in this
position, then ...Nc6 is better than ...Nbd7. The knight is much better placed
and more active on c6 and allows the light-squared bishop to come into play.
The coordination between the pieces is better, and also after ...e5, the
knight will exert pressure on the d4-pawn, which would not be the case if it
was on d7.} 7. Be2 {Please remember the setup of the pieces here. If the
knight is on d7 instead of c6, then the Black position is passive, and it is
better to put the light-squared bishop on the more active d3-square. Here,
with the knight on c6, the White plan is to exchange on e5 later on, after
which this bishop will stand better on e2, not being under attack.} h6 {Black
can play with or without this move. If Black plays ...h6 here or some moves
later, then he intends to decrease the pressure on the d8-h4 diagonal by
chasing away the bishop, and possibly exchange it.} 8. Bh4 e5 {Black has to
play this move, nothing else makes sense here. It is better to play it
immediately and put some pressure on the White center.} 9. dxe5 {And again,
with or without the ...h6 move, we reach the position that could be played in
two completely different ways with either 9. d5 or 9. dxe5. My recommendation
is dxe5. White will get only a slight edge, but his position will be easy to
play without much counter-play from Black. The main plan is to sort out the
center and then play with a symmetrical pawn structure, which is a little bit
better for White because the c3-pawn secures the d4-square and Black's
c6-knight prevents ...c7-c6, so White might use the d5-square for his pieces.
Also, the Black queen and rooks have to get into play, which will take some
time for Black to organize.The other option for White is 9. d5 with play on
the queenside. The position is completely different and leads to some
extremely complex and difficult play with a race where White plays on the
queenside and Black on the kingside. We will not go any deeper into that
position, as it requires a lot of time to study, and it would be very
unpleasant to play against Black's kingside attack anyways.} dxe5 10. O-O Qe7 {
Black's queen is best on e7 where it supports the e5-pawn and gets away from
potential attacks on the d-file. Also, now the d8-square is free for the Black
rook.} 11. b4 {White's main plan regardless of Black's ...h6-move in these
positions is to play on the queenside. The easiest way to do it is to
immediately get the initiative by playing b4 and a4.} g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Nc4 {
White would like to get the knight from d2 to its best e3 square via c4. From
e3, the knight controls the important f5 and d5 light squares. Please note,
that this is not possible if Black plays ...Be6 before ...Qe7, but in that
case White would first play Bc4 to exchange the light-squared bishops and then
would carry out the knight maneuver.} Nf4 14. Ne3 {White's position is again
slightly better. His pieces are a little bit better and he can start the play
on the queenside first. The main plan should be Qc2, Rfd1 and Nd5 at some
point.} *

